				<connector uid="1" polarity="+" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="222.339">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
Construction is calculated as a fraction of the existing housing stock.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Positive polarity because stock and construction move in the same direction.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>Construction is calculated as a fraction of the existing housing stock.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Positive polarity because stock and construction move in the same direction.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>Housing_Stock</from>
					<to>construction</to>
				</connector>
				<connector uid="2" polarity="+" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="37.4216">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
Demolition is calculated as a fraction of the existing housing stock.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Positive polarity because stock and demolition move in the same direction.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>Demolition is calculated as a fraction of the existing housing stock.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Positive polarity because stock and demolition move in the same direction.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>Housing_Stock</from>
					<to>demolition</to>
				</connector>
				<connector uid="3" polarity="+" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="123.789">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
A higher base construction fraction increases the construction rate.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Positive polarity because fraction and construction move in the same direction.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>A higher base construction fraction increases the construction rate.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Positive polarity because fraction and construction move in the same direction.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>base_construction_fraction</from>
					<to>construction</to>
				</connector>
				<connector uid="4" polarity="+" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="93.2773">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
A higher demolition fraction increases the demolition rate.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Positive polarity because fraction and demolition move in the same direction.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>A higher demolition fraction increases the demolition rate.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Positive polarity because fraction and demolition move in the same direction.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>demolition_fraction</from>
					<to>demolition</to>
				</connector>
				<connector uid="5" polarity="+" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="328.88">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
A higher construction multiplier increases the construction rate.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Positive polarity because multiplier and construction move in the same direction.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>A higher construction multiplier increases the construction rate.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Positive polarity because multiplier and construction move in the same direction.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>construction_multiplier</from>
					<to>construction</to>
				</connector>
				<connector uid="6" polarity="+" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="131.997">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
Higher relative demand for housing encourages more construction.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Positive polarity because demand and multiplier move in the same direction.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>Higher relative demand for housing encourages more construction.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Positive polarity because demand and multiplier move in the same direction.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>relative_housing_demand</from>
					<to>construction_multiplier</to>
				</connector>
				<connector uid="7" polarity="+" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="112.762">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
A larger population increases the demand for housing.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Positive polarity because population and demand move in the same direction.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>A larger population increases the demand for housing.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Positive polarity because population and demand move in the same direction.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>Population</from>
					<to>relative_housing_demand</to>
				</connector>
				<connector uid="8" polarity="-" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="224.503">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
More housing stock decreases the relative demand for new housing.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Negative polarity because stock and demand move in opposite directions.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>More housing stock decreases the relative demand for new housing.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Negative polarity because stock and demand move in opposite directions.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>Housing_Stock</from>
					<to>relative_housing_demand</to>
				</connector>
				<connector uid="9" polarity="-" isee:polarity_placement="outside" angle="21.5321">
					<isee:documentation>Reasoning:
A higher target for persons per house makes the current demand look lower relatively.

Polarity Reasoning: 
Negative polarity because target and relative demand move in opposite directions.</isee:documentation>
					<isee:reasoning>A higher target for persons per house makes the current demand look lower relatively.</isee:reasoning>
					<isee:polarity_reasoning>Negative polarity because target and relative demand move in opposite directions.</isee:polarity_reasoning>
					<from>target_persons_per_house</from>
					<to>relative_housing_demand</to>
				</connector>
			</view>
		</views>
	</model>
	<model name="Population">
		<variables>
			<flow name="births" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The number of new residents born per year.</doc>
				<eqn>Population*birth_fraction</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>people/years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="deaths" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The number of residents who die per year.</doc>
				<eqn>Population*death_fraction</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>people/years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="migration" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The net movement of people into or out of the urban area based on housing and job availability.</doc>
				<eqn>Population*base_migration_fraction*((attractiveness_from_housing+attractiveness_from_jobs)/2)</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>people/years</units>
			</flow>
			<aux name="birth fraction" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The annual birth rate per person.</doc>
				<eqn>0.02</eqn>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="death fraction" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The annual death rate per person.</doc>
				<eqn>0.015</eqn>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="base migration fraction" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The normal net migration rate under balanced conditions.</doc>
				<eqn>0.01</eqn>
				<units>1/year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="target housing per person" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The desired ratio of housing units per resident.</doc>
				<eqn>0.4</eqn>
				<units>units/person</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="target jobs per person" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The desired ratio of jobs per resident.</doc>
				<eqn>1</eqn>
				<units>jobs/person</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="relative housing availability" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The ratio of actual housing per person to the target housing per person.</doc>
				<eqn>(Housing_Stock/Population)//target_housing_per_person</eqn>
				<units>dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="relative job availability" ai_state="C">
				<doc>The ratio of actual jobs per person to the target jobs per person.</doc>
				<eqn>(total_jobs/Population)//target_jobs_per_person</eqn>
				<units>dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="attractiveness from housing" ai_state="C">
				<doc>A multiplier representing how housing availability influences migration.</doc>
				<eqn>relative_housing_availability</eqn>
				<gf>
					<yscale min="0" max="1.5"/>
					<xpts>0,0.5,1,1.5,2</xpts>
					<ypts>0,0.5,1,1.3,1.5</ypts>
				</gf>
				<units>dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="attractiveness from jobs" ai_state="C">
				<doc>A multiplier representing how job availability influences migration.</doc>
				<eqn>relative_job_availability</eqn>
				<gf>
					<yscale min="0" max="1.5"/>
					<xpts>0,0.5,1,1.5,2</xpts>
					<ypts>0,0.5,1,1.3,1.5</ypts>
				</gf>
				<units>dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<stock name="Population" ai_state="C" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<doc>The total number of residents in the urban area.</doc>
				<eqn>10000</eqn>
				<inflow>births</inflow>
				<inflow>migration</inflow>
				<outflow>deaths</outflow>
				<units>people</units>
			</stock>
			<stock name="Housing Stock" ai_state="C" access="input">
				<eqn>4000</eqn>
				<units>units</units>
			</stock>
			<aux name="total jobs" ai_state="C" access="input">
				<eqn>{Enter equation for use when not hooked up to other models}</eqn>
				<units>jobs</units>
			</aux>
		</variables>
